quoteText:
Listen, Robert, dear. Let me tell you something. You won't mind, will
you? Don't have scenes with your young ladies. Try not to. Because you
can't have scenes without crying, and then you pity yourself so much you
can't remember what the other person's said. You'll never be able to
remember any conversations that way. Just try and be calm. I know it's
awfully hard. But remember, it's for literature. We all ought to make
sacrifices for literature. Look at me. I'm going to England without a
protest. All for literature. We must all help young writers. Don't you
think so, Jake? But you're not a young writer. Are you, Robert? You're
thirty-four. Still, I suppose that is young for a great writer. Look at
Hardy. Look at Anatole France. He just died a little while ago. Robert
doesn't think he's any good, though. Some of his French friends told
him. He doesn't read French very well himself. He wasn't a good writer
like you are, was he, Robert? Do you think he ever had to go and look
for material? What do you suppose he said to his mistresses when he
wouldn't marry them? I wonder if he cried, too? Oh, I've just thought of
something.
subQuotationList:
["Listen, Robert, dear. Let me tell you something. You won't mind, will
you? Don't have scenes with your young ladies. Try not to. Because you
can't have scenes without crying, and then you pity yourself so much you
can't remember what the other person's said. You'll never be able to
remember any conversations that way. Just try and be calm. I know it's
awfully hard. But remember, it's for literature. We all ought to make
sacrifices for literature. Look at me. I'm going to England without a
protest. All for literature. We must all help young writers. Don't you
think so, Jake? But you're not a young writer. Are you, Robert? You're
thirty-four. Still, I suppose that is young for a great writer. Look at
Hardy. Look at Anatole France. He just died a little while ago. Robert
doesn't think he's any good, though. Some of his French friends told
him. He doesn't read French very well himself. He wasn't a good writer
like you are, was he, Robert? Do you think he ever had to go and look
for material? What do you suppose he said to his mistresses when he
wouldn't marry them? I wonder if he cried, too? Oh, I've just thought of
something."]

quoteText:
I know the real
reason why Robert won't marry me, Jake. It's just come to me. They've
sent it to me in a vision in the Caf  Select. Isn't it mystic? Some day
they'll put a tablet up. Like at Lourdes. Do you want to hear, Robert?
I'll tell you. It's so simple. I wonder why I never thought about it.
Why, you see, Robert's always wanted to have a mistress, and if he
doesn't marry me, why, then he's had one. She was his mistress for over
two years. See how it is? And if he marries me, like he's always
promised he would, that would be the end of all the romance. Don't you
think that's bright of me to figure that out? It's true, too. Look at
him and see if it's not. Where are you going, Jake?

get his clothes. Wore my coat. Remember the whole thing now. Big
sporting evening.

quoteText: Quite a girl, She's damned nice. Who's Michael?
subQuotationList: ['Quite a girl,', "She's damned nice. Who's Michael?"]
speaker: Bill Gorton

quoteText: The man she's going to marry.
speaker: Jake Barnes

quoteText:
Well, well, That's always just the stage I meet anybody.
What'll I send them? Think they'd like a couple of stuffed race-horses?
subQuotationList: ['Well, well,', "That's always just the stage I meet anybody.\nWhat'll I send them? Think they'd like a couple of stuffed race-horses?"]
speaker: Bill Gorton

quoteText: We better eat.
speaker: Jake Barnes

quoteText: Is she really Lady something or other?
subQuotationList: ['Is she really Lady something or other?']
speaker: Bill Gorton

quoteText: Oh, yes. In the stud-book and everything.
subQuotationList: ['Oh, yes. In the stud-book and everything.']
speaker: Jake Barnes

quoteText: Well, well.
speaker: Bill Gorton

quoteText: Doesn't get us a table, though, Grand woman, though.
subQuotationList: ["Doesn't get us a table, though,", 'Grand woman, though.']
speaker: Bill Gorton

quoteText: You've got the world here all right,
subQuotationList: ["You've got the world here all right,"]
speaker: Bill Gorton

quoteText: Oh, my God!
speaker: Madame Lecomte

quoteText: You'll be rich.
speaker: Bill Gorton

quoteText: I hope so.
speaker: Madame Lecomte

quoteText: You never come here any more, Monsieur Barnes,
subQuotationList: ['You never come here any more, Monsieur Barnes,']
speaker: Madame Lecomte

quoteText: Too many compatriots.
speaker: Jake Barnes

quoteText: Come at lunch-time. It's not crowded then.
subQuotationList: ["Come at lunch-time. It's not crowded then."]
speaker: Madame Lecomte

quoteText: Good. I'll be down soon.
speaker: Jake Barnes

quoteText: They're going to cut a street through.
subQuotationList: ["They're going to cut a street through."]
speaker: Jake Barnes

quoteText: They would, It's pretty grand, God, I love to get back.
subQuotationList: ['They would,', "It's pretty grand,", 'God, I love to get back.']
speaker: Bill Gorton

quoteText: Want to have a drink?
speaker: Jake Barnes

quoteText: No, I don't need it.
speaker: Bill Gorton

quoteText:
What do you want to do? Go up to the caf  and see Brett and
Mike?
subQuotationList: ['What do you want to do?', 'Go up to the caf  and see Brett and\nMike?']
speaker: Jake Barnes

quoteText: Why not?
speaker: Bill Gorton

quoteText: Hel-lo, Jake, Hel-lo! Hel-lo! How are you, old lad?
subQuotationList: ['Hel-lo, Jake,', 'Hel-lo! Hel-lo! How are you, old lad?']
speaker: Mike Campbell

quoteText: You look very fit, Mike.
speaker: Jake Barnes

quoteText:
Oh, I am. I'm frightfully fit. I've done nothing but walk. Walk all day
long. One drink a day with my mother at tea.
subQuotationList: ["Oh, I am. I'm frightfully fit. I've done nothing but walk. Walk all day\nlong. One drink a day with my mother at tea."]
speaker: Mike Campbell

quoteText:
It's good to see you, Jake, I'm a little tight you
know. Amazing, isn't it? Did you see my nose?
subQuotationList: ["It's good to see you, Jake,", "I'm a little tight you\nknow. Amazing, isn't it? Did you see my nose?"]
speaker: Mike Campbell

quoteText:
An old lady's bags did that, I reached up to help her with
them and they fell on me.
subQuotationList: ["An old lady's bags did that,", 'I reached up to help her with\nthem and they fell on me.']
speaker: Mike Campbell

quoteText:
An old lady, Her bags _fell_ on me. Let's go in and see
Brett. I say, she is a piece.
subQuotationList: ['An old lady,', "Her bags _fell_ on me. Let's go in and see\nBrett. I say, she is a piece."]
speaker: Mike Campbell

quoteText:
You _are_ a lovely lady, Brett. Where did
you get that hat?
subQuotationList: ['You _are_ a lovely lady, Brett. Where did\nyou get that hat?']
speaker: Mike Campbell

quoteText: Chap bought it for me. Don't you like it?
subQuotationList: ["Chap bought it for me. Don't you like it?"]
speaker: Brett Ashley

quoteText: It's a dreadful hat. Do get a good hat.
subQuotationList: ["It's a dreadful hat. Do get a good hat."]
speaker: Mike Campbell

quoteText:
Oh, we've so much money now, I say, haven't you met Bill
yet? You _are_ a lovely host, Jake.
subQuotationList: ["Oh, we've so much money now,", "I say, haven't you met Bill\nyet? You _are_ a lovely host, Jake."]
speaker: Brett Ashley
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Mike Campbell', 'Brett Ashley']], [['Mike Campbell'], ['Bill Gorton'], ['Jake Barnes'], ['Jake Barnes']]]

quoteText:
This is Bill Gorton. This drunkard is Mike
Campbell. Mr. Campbell is an undischarged bankrupt.
subQuotationList: ['This is Bill Gorton. This drunkard is Mike\nCampbell. Mr. Campbell is an undischarged bankrupt.']
speaker: Brett Ashley

quoteText:
Aren't I, though? You know I met my ex-partner yesterday in London.
Chap who did me in.
subQuotationList: ["Aren't I, though? You know I met my ex-partner yesterday in London.\nChap who did me in."]
speaker: Mike Campbell

quoteText: What did he say?
speaker: Brett Ashley

quoteText:
Bought me a drink. I thought I might as well take it. I say, Brett, you
_are_ a lovely piece. Don't you think she's beautiful?
subQuotationList: ["Bought me a drink. I thought I might as well take it. I say, Brett, you\n_are_ a lovely piece. Don't you think she's beautiful?"]
speaker: Mike Campbell

quoteText: Beautiful. With this nose?
speaker: Brett Ashley

quoteText: It's a lovely nose. Go on, point it at me. Isn't she a lovely piece?
subQuotationList: ["It's a lovely nose. Go on, point it at me. Isn't she a lovely piece?"]
speaker: Mike Campbell

quoteText: Couldn't we have kept the man in Scotland?
subQuotationList: ["Couldn't we have kept the man in Scotland?"]
speaker: Brett Ashley

quoteText: I say, Brett, let's turn in early.
subQuotationList: ["I say, Brett, let's turn in early."]
speaker: Mike Campbell

quoteText: Don't be indecent, Michael. Remember there are ladies at this bar.
subQuotationList: ["Don't be indecent, Michael. Remember there are ladies at this bar."]
speaker: Brett Ashley

quoteText: Isn't she a lovely piece? Don't you think so, Jake?
subQuotationList: ["Isn't she a lovely piece? Don't you think so, Jake?"]
speaker: Mike Campbell

quoteText: There's a fight to-night, Like to go?
speaker: Bill Gorton

quoteText: Fight, Who's fighting?
speaker: Mike Campbell

quoteText: Ledoux and somebody.
speaker: Bill Gorton

quoteText:
He's very good, Ledoux, I'd like to see it, rather but I can't go. I had a
date with this thing here. I say, Brett, do get a new hat.
subQuotationList: ["He's very good, Ledoux,", "I'd like to see it, rather", "but I can't go. I had a\ndate with this thing here. I say, Brett, do get a new hat."]
speaker: Mike Campbell

quoteText:
You two run along to the fight. I'll have to be taking Mr.
Campbell home directly.
subQuotationList: ["You two run along to the fight. I'll have to be taking Mr.\nCampbell home directly."]
speaker: Brett Ashley

quoteText:
I'm not tight, Perhaps just a little. I say, Brett, you
are a lovely piece.
subQuotationList: ["I'm not tight,", 'Perhaps just a little. I say, Brett, you\nare a lovely piece.']
speaker: Mike Campbell

quoteText:
Go on to the fight, Mr. Campbell's getting difficult.
What are these outbursts of affection, Michael?
subQuotationList: ['Go on to the fight,', "Mr. Campbell's getting difficult.\nWhat are these outbursts of affection, Michael?"]
speaker: Brett Ashley

quoteText: I say, you are a lovely piece.
subQuotationList: ['I say, you are a lovely piece.']
speaker: Mike Campbell

quoteText: I'm sorry I can't go,
speaker: Mike Campbell

quoteText: Do you want to go to the fight?
subQuotationList: ['Do you want to go to the fight?']
speaker: Jake Barnes

quoteText: Sure, If we don't have to walk.
speaker: Bill Gorton

quoteText: Mike was pretty excited about his girl friend,
subQuotationList: ['Mike was pretty excited about his girl friend,']
speaker: Jake Barnes

quoteText: Well, You can't blame him such a hell of a lot.
subQuotationList: ['Well,', "You can't blame him such a hell of a lot."]
speaker: Bill Gorton

quoteText: Hello, darling.
speaker: Brett Ashley

quoteText: Hello, Jake, I understand I was tight last night.
subQuotationList: ['Hello, Jake,', 'I understand I was tight last night.']
speaker: Mike Campbell

quoteText: Weren't you, though, Disgraceful business.
speaker: Brett Ashley

quoteText:
Look, when do you go down to Spain? Would you mind if we
came down with you?
subQuotationList: ['Look,', 'when do you go down to Spain? Would you mind if we\ncame down with you?']
speaker: Mike Campbell

quoteText: It would be grand.
speaker: Jake Barnes

quoteText:
You wouldn't mind, really? I've been at Pamplona, you know. Brett's mad
to go. You're sure we wouldn't just be a bloody nuisance?
subQuotationList: ["You wouldn't mind, really? I've been at Pamplona, you know. Brett's mad\nto go. You're sure we wouldn't just be a bloody nuisance?"]
speaker: Mike Campbell
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Jake Barnes'], ['Jake Barnes'], ['Brett Ashley'], ['Jake Barnes'], ['Mike Campbell', 'Brett Ashley']]]

quoteText: Don't talk like a fool.
speaker: Jake Barnes

quoteText:
I'm a little tight, you know. I wouldn't ask you like this if I
weren't. You're sure you don't mind?
subQuotationList: ["I'm a little tight, you know. I wouldn't ask you like this if I\nweren't. You're sure you don't mind?"]
speaker: Mike Campbell

quoteText:
Oh, shut up, Michael, How can the man say he'd mind now?
I'll ask him later.
subQuotationList: ['Oh, shut up, Michael,', "How can the man say he'd mind now?\nI'll ask him later."]
speaker: Brett Ashley

quoteText: But you don't mind, do you?
speaker: Mike Campbell

quoteText:
Don't ask that again unless you want to make me sore. Bill and I go
down on the morning of the 25th.
subQuotationList: ["Don't ask that again unless you want to make me sore. Bill and I go\ndown on the morning of the 25th."]
speaker: Jake Barnes

quoteText: By the way, where is Bill?
speaker: Brett Ashley

quoteText: He's out at Chantilly dining with some people.
subQuotationList: ["He's out at Chantilly dining with some people."]
speaker: Jake Barnes

quoteText: He's a good chap.
speaker: Brett Ashley

quoteText: Splendid chap, He is, you know.
speaker: Mike Campbell

quoteText: You don't remember him,
speaker: Brett Ashley

quoteText:
I do. Remember him perfectly. Look, Jake, we'll come down the night of
the 25th. Brett can't get up in the morning.
subQuotationList: ["I do. Remember him perfectly. Look, Jake, we'll come down the night of\nthe 25th. Brett can't get up in the morning."]
speaker: Mike Campbell

quoteText: Indeed not!
speaker: Brett Ashley

quoteText: If our money comes and you're sure you don't mind.
subQuotationList: ["If our money comes and you're sure you don't mind."]
speaker: Mike Campbell

quoteText: It will come, all right. I'll see to that.
subQuotationList: ["It will come, all right. I'll see to that."]
speaker: Brett Ashley

quoteText: Tell me what tackle to send for.
subQuotationList: ['Tell me what tackle to send for.']
speaker: Mike Campbell

quoteText: Get two or three rods with reels, and lines, and some flies.
subQuotationList: ['Get two or three rods with reels, and lines, and some flies.']
speaker: Jake Barnes

quoteText: I won't fish,
speaker: Brett Ashley

quoteText: Get two rods, then, and Bill won't have to buy one.
subQuotationList: ["Get two rods, then, and Bill won't have to buy one."]
speaker: Jake Barnes

quoteText: Right, I'll send a wire to the keeper.
subQuotationList: ['Right,', "I'll send a wire to the keeper."]
speaker: Mike Campbell

quoteText: Won't it be splendid, Spain! We _will_ have fun.
subQuotationList: ["Won't it be splendid,", 'Spain! We _will_ have fun.']
speaker: Brett Ashley

quoteText: The 25th. When is that?
speaker: Brett Ashley

quoteText: Saturday.
speaker: Jake Barnes

quoteText: We _will_ have to get ready.
speaker: Brett Ashley

quoteText: I say, I'm going to the barber's.
speaker: Mike Campbell

quoteText:
I must bathe, Walk up to the hotel with me, Jake. Be a
good chap.
subQuotationList: ['I must bathe,', 'Walk up to the hotel with me, Jake. Be a\ngood chap.']
speaker: Brett Ashley

quoteText:
We _have_ got the loveliest hotel, I think it's a
brothel!
subQuotationList: ['We _have_ got the loveliest hotel,', "I think it's a\nbrothel!"]
speaker: Mike Campbell

quoteText:
We left our bags here at the Dingo when we got in, and they asked us at
this hotel if we wanted a room for the afternoon only. Seemed
frightfully pleased we were going to stay all night.
subQuotationList: ['We left our bags here at the Dingo when we got in, and they asked us at\nthis hotel if we wanted a room for the afternoon only. Seemed\nfrightfully pleased we were going to stay all night.']
speaker: Brett Ashley
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Mike Campbell', 'Brett Ashley'], ['Mike Campbell', 'Brett Ashley'], ['Mike Campbell', 'Brett Ashley'], ['Mike Campbell', 'Brett Ashley'], ['Mike Campbell', 'Brett Ashley']]]

quoteText: _I_ believe it's a brothel, And _I_ should know.
subQuotationList: ["_I_ believe it's a brothel,", 'And _I_ should know.']
speaker: Mike Campbell

quoteText: Oh, shut it and go and get your hair cut.
subQuotationList: ['Oh, shut it and go and get your hair cut.']
speaker: Brett Ashley

quoteText: I needed that, I haven't seen you since I've been back,
subQuotationList: ['I needed that,', "I haven't seen you since I've been back,"]
speaker: Brett Ashley

quoteText: No.
speaker: Jake Barnes

quoteText: How _are_ you, Jake?
speaker: Brett Ashley

quoteText: Fine.
speaker: Jake Barnes

quoteText:
I say, is Robert Cohn going on this
trip?
subQuotationList: ['I say,', 'is Robert Cohn going on this\ntrip?']
speaker: Brett Ashley

quoteText: Yes. Why?
speaker: Jake Barnes

quoteText: Don't you think it will be a bit rough on him?
subQuotationList: ["Don't you think it will be a bit rough on him?"]
speaker: Brett Ashley

quoteText: Why should it?
speaker: Jake Barnes

quoteText: Who did you think I went down to San Sebastian with?
subQuotationList: ['Who did you think I went down to San Sebastian with?']
speaker: Brett Ashley

quoteText: Congratulations,
speaker: Jake Barnes

quoteText: What did you say that for?
speaker: Brett Ashley

quoteText: I don't know. What would you like me to say?
subQuotationList: ["I don't know. What would you like me to say?"]
speaker: Jake Barnes

quoteText: He behaved rather well, too. He gets a little dull.
subQuotationList: ['He behaved rather well, too. He gets a little dull.']
speaker: Brett Ashley

quoteText: Does he?
speaker: Jake Barnes

quoteText: I rather thought it would be good for him.
subQuotationList: ['I rather thought it would be good for him.']
speaker: Brett Ashley

quoteText: You might take up social service.
speaker: Jake Barnes

quoteText: Don't be nasty.
speaker: Brett Ashley

quoteText: I won't.
speaker: Jake Barnes

quoteText: Didn't you really know?
speaker: Brett Ashley

quoteText: No, I guess I didn't think about it.
subQuotationList: ['No,', "I guess I didn't think about it."]
speaker: Jake Barnes

quoteText: Do you think it will be too rough on him?
subQuotationList: ['Do you think it will be too rough on him?']
speaker: Brett Ashley

quoteText:
That's up to him, Tell him you're coming. He can always not
come.
subQuotationList: ["That's up to him,", "Tell him you're coming. He can always not\ncome."]
speaker: Jake Barnes

quoteText: I'll write him and give him a chance to pull out of it.
subQuotationList: ["I'll write him and give him a chance to pull out of it."]
speaker: Brett Ashley

quoteText: Did you hear from Cohn?
speaker: Jake Barnes

quoteText: Rather. He's keen about it.
speaker: Brett Ashley

quoteText: My God!
speaker: Jake Barnes

quoteText: I thought it was rather odd myself.
subQuotationList: ['I thought it was rather odd myself.']
speaker: Brett Ashley

quoteText: Says he can't wait to see me.
subQuotationList: ["Says he can't wait to see me."]
speaker: Brett Ashley

quoteText: Does he think you're coming alone?
speaker: Jake Barnes

quoteText: No. I told him we were all coming down together. Michael and all.
subQuotationList: ['No. I told him we were all coming down together. Michael and all.']
speaker: Brett Ashley

quoteText: He's wonderful.
speaker: Jake Barnes

quoteText: Isn't he?
speaker: Brett Ashley

quoteText: Nothing until the fifth.
speaker: The Conductor

quoteText: What's this?
speaker: Jake Barnes

quoteText:
They're all reserved, There will be a
fifth service at three-thirty.
subQuotationList: ["They're all reserved,", 'There will be a\nfifth service at three-thirty.']
speaker: The Conductor

quoteText: This is serious,
speaker: Jake Barnes

quoteText: Give him ten francs.
speaker: Bill Gorton

quoteText: Here, We want to eat in the first service.
subQuotationList: ['Here,', 'We want to eat in the first service.']
speaker: Jake Barnes

quoteText:
Thank you, I would advise you gentlemen to get some
sandwiches. All the places for the first four services were reserved at
the office of the company.
subQuotationList: ['Thank you,', 'I would advise you gentlemen to get some\nsandwiches. All the places for the first four services were reserved at\nthe office of the company.']
speaker: The Conductor

quoteText:
You'll go a long way, brother, I suppose
if I'd given you five francs you would have advised us to jump off the
train.
subQuotationList: ["You'll go a long way, brother,", "I suppose\nif I'd given you five francs you would have advised us to jump off the\ntrain."]
speaker: Bill Gorton
mentionEntitiesList: [[['The Conductor'], ['The Conductor']], [['The Conductor'], ['The Conductor'], ['Jake Barnes', 'Bill Gorton']]]

quoteText: _Comment?_
speaker: The Conductor

quoteText:
Go to hell! Get the sandwiches made and a bottle of wine.
You tell him, Jake.
subQuotationList: ['Go to hell!', 'Get the sandwiches made and a bottle of wine.\nYou tell him, Jake.']
speaker: Bill Gorton

quoteText: And send it up to the next car.
subQuotationList: ['And send it up to the next car.']
speaker: Jake Barnes

quoteText:
I suppose you're Americans, aren't you? Having a good
trip?
subQuotationList: ["I suppose you're Americans, aren't you?", 'Having a good\ntrip?']
speaker: The Man

quoteText: Wonderful,
speaker: Bill Gorton

quoteText:
That's what you want to do. Travel while you're young. Mother and I
always wanted to get over, but we had to wait a while.
subQuotationList: ["That's what you want to do. Travel while you're young. Mother and I\nalways wanted to get over, but we had to wait a while."]
speaker: The Man
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Jake Barnes', 'Bill Gorton'], ['Jake Barnes', 'Bill Gorton'], ['The Wife', 'The Man']]]

quoteText:
You could have come over ten years ago, if you'd wanted to, What you always said was: I will say we've
seen a good deal, take it one way and another.
subQuotationList: ["You could have come over ten years ago, if you'd wanted to,", 'What you always said was:', "I will say we've\nseen a good deal, take it one way and another."]
speaker: The Wife

quoteText:
Say, there's plenty of Americans on this train, They've got seven cars of them from Dayton, Ohio. They've been on a
pilgrimage to Rome, and now they're going down to Biarritz and Lourdes.
subQuotationList: ["Say, there's plenty of Americans on this train,", "They've got seven cars of them from Dayton, Ohio. They've been on a\npilgrimage to Rome, and now they're going down to Biarritz and Lourdes."]
speaker: The Man

quoteText: So, that's what they are. Pilgrims. Goddam Puritans,
subQuotationList: ["So, that's what they are. Pilgrims. Goddam Puritans,"]
speaker: Bill Gorton

quoteText: What part of the States you boys from?
subQuotationList: ['What part of the States you boys from?']
speaker: The Man

quoteText: Kansas City, He's from Chicago.
speaker: Jake Barnes

quoteText: You both going to Biarritz?
speaker: The Man

quoteText: No. We're going fishing in Spain.
speaker: Jake Barnes

quoteText:
Well, I never cared for it, myself. There's plenty that do out where I
come from, though. We got some of the best fishing in the State of
Montana. I've been out with the boys, but I never cared for it any.
subQuotationList: ["Well, I never cared for it, myself. There's plenty that do out where I\ncome from, though. We got some of the best fishing in the State of\nMontana. I've been out with the boys, but I never cared for it any."]
speaker: The Man

quoteText: Mighty little fishing you did on them trips,
subQuotationList: ['Mighty little fishing you did on them trips,']
speaker: The Wife

quoteText:
You know how the ladies are. If there's a jug goes along, or a case of
beer, they think it's hell and damnation.
subQuotationList: ["You know how the ladies are. If there's a jug goes along, or a case of\nbeer, they think it's hell and damnation."]
speaker: The Man

quoteText:
That's the way men are, I voted against prohibition to please him, and because
I like a little beer in the house, and then he talks that way. It's a
wonder they ever find any one to marry them.
subQuotationList: ["That's the way men are,", "I voted against prohibition to please him, and because\nI like a little beer in the house, and then he talks that way. It's a\nwonder they ever find any one to marry them."]
speaker: The Wife

quoteText:
Say, do you know that gang of Pilgrim Fathers have
cornered the dining-car until half past three this afternoon?
subQuotationList: ['Say,', 'do you know that gang of Pilgrim Fathers have\ncornered the dining-car until half past three this afternoon?']
speaker: Bill Gorton

quoteText: How do you mean? They can't do a thing like that.
subQuotationList: ["How do you mean? They can't do a thing like that."]
speaker: The Man

quoteText: You try and get seats.
speaker: Bill Gorton

quoteText:
Well, mother, it looks as though we better go back and get another
breakfast.
subQuotationList: ['Well, mother, it looks as though we better go back and get another\nbreakfast.']
speaker: The Man

quoteText: Will you boys keep an eye on our things? Come on, Hubert.
subQuotationList: ['Will you boys keep an eye on our things? Come on, Hubert.']
speaker: The Wife

quoteText: You're going to work to-day,
speaker: Jake Barnes

quoteText: They start now, at ten-thirty.
speaker: A Waiter

quoteText: When do we eat?
speaker: Jake Barnes

quoteText: Huh! When do I eat?
speaker: A Waiter

quoteText: I'll get the plates, or bring them with you.
subQuotationList: ["I'll get the plates,", 'or bring them with you.']
speaker: A Waiter

quoteText: Is there good swimming in Biarritz?
speaker: Hubert

quoteText: That boy's just crazy till he can get in the water, It's pretty hard on youngsters travelling.
subQuotationList: ["That boy's just crazy till he can get in the water,", "It's pretty hard on youngsters travelling."]
speaker: The Wife

quoteText: There's good swimming, But it's dangerous when it's rough.
subQuotationList: ["There's good swimming,", "But it's dangerous when it's rough."]
speaker: Jake Barnes

quoteText: Did you get a meal?
speaker: Bill Gorton

quoteText:
We sure did. We set right there when they started to come in, and they
must have just thought we were in the party. One of the waiters said
something to us in French, and then they just sent three of them back.
subQuotationList: ['We sure did. We set right there when they started to come in, and they\nmust have just thought we were in the party. One of the waiters said\nsomething to us in French, and then they just sent three of them back.']
speaker: The Wife
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Hubert', 'The Man', 'The Wife'], ['Hubert', 'The Man', 'The Wife'], ['Hubert', 'The Man', 'The Wife'], ['Hubert', 'The Man', 'The Wife']]]

quoteText:
They thought we were snappers, all right, It certainly
shows you the power of the Catholic Church. It's a pity you boys ain't
Catholics. You could get a meal, then, all right.
subQuotationList: ['They thought we were snappers, all right,', "It certainly\nshows you the power of the Catholic Church. It's a pity you boys ain't\nCatholics. You could get a meal, then, all right."]
speaker: The Man
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Hubert', 'The Man', 'The Wife']], [['Jake Barnes', 'Bill Gorton'], ['Jake Barnes', 'Bill Gorton']]]

quoteText: I am, That's what makes me so sore.
subQuotationList: ['I am,', "That's what makes me so sore."]
speaker: Jake Barnes

quoteText: When do us Protestants get a chance to eat, father?
subQuotationList: ['When do us Protestants get a chance to eat, father?']
speaker: Bill Gorton

quoteText: I don't know anything about it. Haven't you got tickets?
subQuotationList: ["I don't know anything about it. Haven't you got tickets?"]
speaker: A Priest

quoteText: It's enough to make a man join the Klan,
subQuotationList: ["It's enough to make a man join the Klan,"]
speaker: Bill Gorton

quoteText: Well, I hope you have lots of luck,
subQuotationList: ['Well, I hope you have lots of luck,']
speaker: The Man

quoteText: Be careful about those bull-fights.
speaker: The Wife

quoteText: Maybe we'll see you at Biarritz,
speaker: Hubert

quoteText: Hello, Jake. Have a good trip?
speaker: Robert Cohn

quoteText: Fine, This is Bill Gorton.
speaker: Jake Barnes

quoteText: How are you?
speaker: Bill Gorton

quoteText: Come on, I've got a cab.
speaker: Robert Cohn

quoteText: We'll go up to my hotel. It's all right. It's quite nice.

speaker: Bill Gorton

quoteText: I say, Barnes. You don't know what this all means to me.
subQuotationList: ["I say, Barnes. You don't know what this all means to me."]

quoteText: Come on and utilize another glass,
speaker: Jake Barnes

quoteText: Barnes. Really, Barnes, you can't know. That's all.
subQuotationList: ["Barnes. Really, Barnes, you can't know. That's all."]
speaker: Harris

quoteText: Drink up, Harris.
speaker: Jake Barnes

quoteText: I say, Harris--
speaker: Jake Barnes

quoteText:
No, no! They're not
first-rate flies at all. I only thought if you fished them some time it
might remind you of what a good time we had.
subQuotationList: ['No, no!', "They're not\nfirst-rate flies at all. I only thought if you fished them some time it\nmight remind you of what a good time we had."]
speaker: Harris

quoteText: Say, wasn't that Harris nice?
speaker: Bill Gorton

quoteText: I think he really did have a good time.
subQuotationList: ['I think he really did have a good time.']
speaker: Jake Barnes

quoteText: Harris? You bet he did.
speaker: Bill Gorton

quoteText: I wish he'd come into Pamplona.
speaker: Jake Barnes

quoteText: He wanted to fish.
speaker: Bill Gorton

quoteText: Yes. You couldn't tell how English would mix with each other, anyway.
subQuotationList: ["Yes. You couldn't tell how English would mix with each other, anyway."]
speaker: Jake Barnes

quoteText: I suppose not.

quoteText: Mr. Campbell?

subQuotationList: ['Yes. Mr. Cohn and Mr. Campbell and Lady Ashley.']

quoteText: Yesterday. I've saved you the rooms you had.

speaker: Montoya

subQuotationList: ["That's fine. Did you give Mr. Campbell the room on the plaza?"]

subQuotationList: ['Yes. All the rooms we looked at.']
speaker: Montoya

quoteText:
To-night, To-night at seven o'clock they
bring in the Villar bulls, and to-morrow come the Miuras. Do you all go
down?
subQuotationList: ['To-night,', "To-night at seven o'clock they\nbring in the Villar bulls, and to-morrow come the Miuras. Do you all go\ndown?"]

subQuotationList: ["Oh, yes. They've never seen a desencajonada."]

quoteText: I'll see you there.

quoteText: Yes. He came all the way from New York to see the San Fermines.
subQuotationList: ['Yes. He came all the way from New York to see the San Fermines.']

quoteText: Yes? But he's not aficionado like you.
speaker: Montoya

quoteText: Yes, He's a real aficionado.
speaker: Jake Barnes

quoteText: But he's not aficionado like you are.
subQuotationList: ["But he's not aficionado like you are."]
speaker: Montoya

quoteText: Well, talk a lot of Spanish?

quoteText: He was telling me about the bulls coming in to-night.
subQuotationList: ['He was telling me about the bulls coming in to-night.']
speaker: Jake Barnes

quoteText: Let's find the gang and go down.
subQuotationList: ["Let's find the gang and go down."]

quoteText: All right. They'll probably be at the caf .
subQuotationList: ["All right. They'll probably be at the caf ."]
speaker: Jake Barnes

quoteText: Have you got tickets?
speaker: Bill Gorton

quoteText: Yes. I got them for all the unloadings.
subQuotationList: ['Yes. I got them for all the unloadings.']
speaker: Jake Barnes

quoteText: What's it like?

quoteText:
It's pretty good, They let the bulls out of the cages one at
a time, and they have steers in the corral to receive them and keep them
from fighting, and the bulls tear in at the steers and the steers run
around like old maids trying to quiet them down.
subQuotationList:
["It's pretty good,", 'They let the bulls out of the cages one at
a time, and they have steers in the corral to receive them and keep them
from fighting, and the bulls tear in at the steers and the steers run
around like old maids trying to quiet them down.']

quoteText: Sure. Sometimes they go right after them and kill them.
subQuotationList: ['Sure. Sometimes they go right after them and kill them.']
speaker: Jake Barnes

quoteText: Can't the steers do anything?

quoteText: No. They're trying to make friends.
speaker: Jake Barnes

quoteText: What do they have them in for?
subQuotationList: ['What do they have them in for?']
speaker: Bill Gorton

To quiet down the bulls and keep them from breaking horns against the
stone walls, or goring each other.
subQuotationList: ['To quiet down the bulls and keep them from breaking horns against the\nstone walls, or goring each other.']
speaker: Jake Barnes

quoteText: Must be swell being a steer.
speaker: Bill Gorton

quoteText: Hello, you chaps!
speaker: Brett Ashley

quoteText: Where the hell have you been?

quoteText: I brought them up here,
speaker: Robert Cohn

quoteText:
What rot, We'd have gotten here earlier if you hadn't
come.
subQuotationList: ['What rot,', "We'd have gotten here earlier if you hadn't\ncome."]
speaker: Brett Ashley

quoteText: You'd never have gotten here.
speaker: Robert Cohn

quoteText: What rot! You chaps are brown. Look at Bill.
subQuotationList: ['What rot! You chaps are brown. Look at Bill.']
speaker: Brett Ashley

quoteText: Did you get good fishing? We wanted to join you.
subQuotationList: ['Did you get good fishing?', 'We wanted to join you.']

subQuotationList: ['I wanted to come,', 'but I thought I ought to bring them.']
speaker: Robert Cohn

quoteText: You bring us. What rot.
speaker: Brett Ashley

quoteText: Was it really good? Did you take many?
subQuotationList: ['Was it really good?', 'Did you take many?']

subQuotationList: ['Some days we took a dozen apiece. There was an Englishman up there.']
speaker: Jake Barnes

quoteText:
Named Harris, Ever know him, Mike? He was in the war,
too.
subQuotationList: ['Named Harris,', 'Ever know him, Mike? He was in the war,\ntoo.']
speaker: Bill Gorton

quoteText:
Fortunate fellow, What times we had. How I wish those dear
days were back.
subQuotationList: ['Fortunate fellow,', 'What times we had. How I wish those dear\ndays were back.']

quoteText: Don't be an ass.

quoteText: Was I not.

He was a very distinguished soldier, Tell them about the

quoteText: I'll not. I've told that four times.
subQuotationList: ["I'll not. I've told that four times."]

quoteText: You never told me,

quoteText: I'll not tell that story. It reflects discredit on me.

speaker: Mike Campbell

quoteText:
Brett will tell you. She tells all the stories that reflect discredit

quoteText:
I suppose I've the usual medals. But I never sent in for them. One time
there was this wopping big dinner and the Prince of Wales was to be
there, and the cards said medals will be worn. So naturally I had no
medals, and I stopped at my tailor's and he was impressed by the
invitation, and I thought that's a good piece of business, and I said to
him:
subQuotationList:
["I suppose I've the usual medals. But I never sent in for them. One time
there was this wopping big dinner and the Prince of Wales was to be
there, and the cards said medals will be worn. So naturally I had no

invitation, and I thought that's a good piece of business, and I said to

quoteText: He said:
speaker: Mike Campbell

quoteText: And I said:
speaker: Mike Campbell

quoteText:
So he
said:
speaker: Mike Campbell

quoteText: And I said:
speaker: Mike Campbell

quoteText: Did he think I spent all my time reading the bloody gazette?
subQuotationList: ['Did he think I spent all my time reading the bloody gazette?']

So he got me some medals, you
know, miniature medals, and handed me the box, and I put it in my pocket
and forgot it. Well, I went to the dinner, and it was the night they'd
shot Henry Wilson, so the Prince didn't come and the King didn't come,
and no one wore any medals, and all these coves were busy taking off
their medals, and I had mine in my pocket.
subQuotationList:
["So he got me some medals, you
know, miniature medals, and handed me the box, and I put it in my pocket
and forgot it. Well, I went to the dinner, and it was the night they'd
shot Henry Wilson, so the Prince didn't come and the King didn't come,
and no one wore any medals, and all these coves were busy taking off
their medals, and I had mine in my pocket."]

quoteText: Is that all?
speaker: Robert Cohn

quoteText: That's all. Perhaps I didn't tell it right.
subQuotationList: ["That's all. Perhaps I didn't tell it right."]

quoteText: You didn't, But no matter.

quoteText:
Ah, yes, I know now. It was a damn dull dinner, and I
couldn't stick it, so I left. Later on in the evening I found the box in
my pocket. I said. Bloody military medals? So I cut
them all off their backing--you know, they put them on a strip--and gave
them all around. Gave one to each girl. Form of souvenir. They thought I
was hell's own shakes of a soldier. Give away medals in a night club.
Dashing fellow.
subQuotationList:
['Ah, yes,', "I know now. It was a damn dull dinner, and I
couldn't stick it, so I left. Later on in the evening I found the box in

Don't you think that was funny? It
was. I swear it was. Any rate, my tailor wrote me and wanted the medals

subQuotationList:
["Don't you think that was funny?", "It

You don't mean it, I should think it would have been grand

Frightfully good tailor. Never believe it to see me now, I
used to pay him a hundred pounds a year just to keep him quiet. So he
wouldn't send me any bills. Frightful blow to him when I went bankrupt.
It was right after the medals. Gave his letters rather a bitter tone.
subQuotationList:
['Frightfully good tailor. Never believe it to see me now,', "I
used to pay him a hundred pounds a year just to keep him quiet. So he

quoteText: Two ways, Gradually and then suddenly.

quoteText: What brought it on?

quoteText:
Friends, I had a lot of friends. False friends. Then I had

quoteText:
Extraordinary thing, Met my former partner the other day.

subQuotationList: ['Extraordinary thing,', 'Met my former partner the other day.\nOffered to buy me a drink.']

I will not, My learned counsel was blind, too. I say this

subQuotationList: ['I will not,', 'My learned counsel was blind, too. I say this\nis a gloomy subject. Are we going down and see these bulls unloaded or\nnot?']

quoteText: That's where we'll go when funds get low,
subQuotationList: ["That's where we'll go when funds get low,"]

quoteText: Look up there,

quoteText: They must think something is going to happen,
subQuotationList: ['They must think something is going to happen,']
speaker: Brett Ashley

quoteText: They want to see the bulls.

quoteText: Why don't they start?

quoteText: They don't look happy, My God, isn't he beautiful?

quoteText:
Look how he knows how to use his horns, He's got a left and a
right just like a boxer.
subQuotationList: ['Look how he knows how to use his horns,', "He's got a left and a\nright just like a boxer."]

quoteText: Not really?
speaker: Brett Ashley

quoteText: You watch.
speaker: Jake Barnes

quoteText: It goes too fast.
speaker: Brett Ashley

quoteText: Wait. There'll be another one in a minute.
subQuotationList: ["Wait. There'll be another one in a minute."]
speaker: Jake Barnes

quoteText: Don't look,
speaker: Jake Barnes

quoteText: That's an extraordinary business,

They all know each other, They're only dangerous when they're

What do you mean, dangerous? They all looked dangerous to

They only want to kill when they're alone. Of course, if you went in

dangerous.

That's too complicated, Don't you ever detach me from the

I say, they _were_ fine bulls, weren't they? Did you see
their horns?

quoteText: Did I not, I had no idea what they were like.

quoteText:
Did you see the one hit that steer? That was

subQuotationList: ['Did you see the one hit that steer?', 'That was\nextraordinary.']

Don't you think so? I would have thought you'd loved being

They lead such a quiet life. They never say anything and they're always

I should think you'd love it. You'd never have to say a word. Come on,

Oh, say something more. Say something funny. Can't you see we're all

I can't blame them. Can you blame them? Why do you follow Brett around?

subQuotationList: ["Don't go,", "Robert Cohn's going to buy a drink."]
speaker: Mike Campbell

quoteText:
Mark you. Brett's had affairs with men before. She tells me all about

read them.

No, listen, Jake. Brett's gone off with men. But they weren't ever
